elements.content: Five new coordination polymers, namely, [Cd(L)0.5(HBTC)]·0.2H2O (1), [Cd3(L)2(BTA)2(H2O)2]·H2O (2), [Cd2(L)0.5(BTEC)]·H2O (3), [Zn3(L)(BTC)2(H2O)2]·3H2O (4), and [Zn2(μ2-OH)(L)0.5(BTA)]·H2O (5) were synthesized under hydrothermal conditions by reactions of corresponding Cd(II) or Zn(II) salts with the mixed multidentate ligands of 1,2,4,5-tetrakis(imidazol-1-ylmethyl)benzene (L) and 1,3,5-benzenetricarboxylic acid (H3BTC), 1,3,5-benzenetriacetic acid (H3BTA), 1,2,4,5-benzenetetracarboxylic acid (H4BTEC), respectively. The complexes were characterized by single crystal X-ray diffraction, IR, and thermogravimetric and elemental analyses. The Cd(II) complex 1 is a two-dimensional (2D) network with infinite one-dimensional (1D) Cd-HBTC2− chains linked together by L ligands, while the Zn(II) complex 4 with the same mixed ligands has a three-dimensional (3D) structure. The Cd(II) complex with BTA3− and L ligands (2) features an unusual 3D framework, and the Zn(II) complex 5 shows a 3D structure with (63)2(42,84)(4,63,86)2 topology. Complex 3 possesses a 3D structure consisting of a Cd-BTEC4− framework and Cd2O2-L 1D chain. The results showed that the coordination geometry of metal centers and the conformation and coordination mode of organic ligands play an important role in determining the structure and topology of the complexes. The luminescence properties of 1−5 were studied in the solid state at room temperature.

Introduction

In recent years, there is great interest in metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) not only because of their intriguing variety of structures and topologies, but also due to their interesting properties and potential applications in ion exchange, catalysis, and optical, magnetic, and porous materials. However, it is still a great challenge to predict the exact structures and composition of the assembly products, and further studies are required to understand the assembly process of metal salts and organic linkers.

elements.content: The results of our previous studies showed that multidentate ligands with arene core and imidazole coordination groups, such as 1-(imidazol-1-yl)-4-(imidazol-1-ylmethyl)benzene, 1,3,5-tris(imidazol-1-yl)benzene, 1,3-bis(imidazol-1-yl)-5-(imidazol-1-ylmethyl)benzene, 1-(imidazol-1-yl)-3,5-bis(imidazol-1-ylmethyl)benzene, 1,3,5-tris(imidazol-1-ylmethyl)-2,4,6-trimethylbenzene, and 1,2,4,5-tetrakis(imidazol-1-ylmethyl)benzene, are versatile in construction of MOFs with specific structures and interesting properties. On the other hand, multicarboxylic compounds, for example, 1,4-benzenedicarboxylic acid, 1,3,5-benzenetricarboxylic acid (H3BTC), 1,3,5-benzenetriacetic acid (H3BTA), and 1,2,4,5-benzenetetracarboxylic acid (H4BTEC), have been demonstrated to be powerful organic ligands, owing to their various coordination modes leading to the formation of diverse structures, as well as their ability to act as hydrogen bonding acceptors and donors in the assembly of supramolecular structures. Taking these results into account, the present study was carried out by a mixing ligands strategy using 1,2,4,5-tetrakis(imidazol-1-ylmethyl)benzene (L) together with H3BTC, H3BTA, or H4BTEC. The flexible multidentate ligand L can adopt different conformations (Scheme ) when it interacts with metal centers, and in addition the multicarboxylate ligand can have varied coordination modes, which will lead to the formation of MOFs with diverse structures and topologies. Although there are reported studies based on bis(imidazole)-containing and multicarboxylate mixed ligands in the construction of multidimensional frameworks, as far as we know, metal complexes with a flexible tetra-imidazole containing ligand and multicarboxylic acids have not been documented so far. Herein, we report the syntheses and crystal structures of five new Zn(II) and Cd(II) coordination complexes [Cd(L)0.5(HBTC)]·0.2H2O (1), [Cd3(L)2(BTA)2(H2O)2]·H2O (2), [Cd2(L)0.5(BTEC)]·H2O (3), [Zn3(L)(BTC)2(H2O)2]·3H2O (4), [Zn2(μ2-OH)(L)0.5(BTA)]·H2O (5). All the compounds were characterized by elemental analysis, X-ray crystallography, and thermogravimetric analysis. The photoluminescence of 1−5 were investigated in the solid state at room temperature.

FT-IR spectra were recorded in the range of 400−4000 cm−1 on a Bruker Vector22 FT-IR spectrophotometer using KBr pellets. The luminescence spectra for the powdered solid samples were measured on an Aminco Bowman Series 2 spectrofluorometer with a xenon arc lamp as the light source. In the measurements of emission and excitation spectra the pass width is 5 nm, and all the measurements were carried out under the same experimental conditions.

Experimental Section

All chemicals and solvents were purchased from commercial sources and used as received without further purification. The ligand L was synthesized according to the method reported previously. Elemental analyses for C, H, and N were performed on a Perkin-Elmer 240C Elemental Analyzer at the analysis center of Nanjing University. Thermogravimetric analyses (TGA) were performed on a TGA V5.1A Dupont 2100 instrument heating from room temperature to 700 °C under N2 with a heating rate of 10 °C/min. FT-IR spectra were recorded in the range of 400-4000 cm-1 on a Bruker Vector22 FT-IR spectrophotometer using KBr pellets. The luminescence spectra for the powdered solid samples were measured on an Aminco Bowman Series 2 spectrofluorometer with a xenon arc lamp as the light source. In the measurements of emission and excitation spectra the pass width is 5 nm, and all the measurements were carried out under the same experimental conditions.

elements.content: In contrast to the partial deprotonation of H3BTC in 1, the H3BTA ligand in 2 is completely deprotonated and BTA3− adopts a μ4-bridging mode to connect four Cd(II) atoms. Two of the three carboxylate groups are in a μ1-η1:η1 chelating mode and the third one is in a μ2-η2:η1-bridging mode (Type II, Scheme ). Ligand L in 2 also adopts an H-type conformation which is the same as that in 1 and links four Cd2 atoms to form an infinite 1D chain. Then the 1D chains are linked together by Cd1−O coordination bonds to generate an infinite 2D network (Figure b). Finally, such 2D networks are connected by BTA3− to form a 3D architecture (Figure c). The most striking feature of 2 is that there are Cd2−O−Cd1−O−Cd2 trinuclear (Cd3O2) subunits (Figure b). Thus, if the trinuclear Cd3O2 unit is considered as a node, which connects six BTA3− ligands, and in turn each BTA3− ligand links three Cd3O2 units, then the Cd(II)-BTA3− structure can be defined as a (3,6)-connected framework with (42·6)2(44·62·88·10) topology (Figure d). In addition, each L ligand connects four Cd3O2 units, and accordingly the whole structure of 2 can be simplified to a new (3,4,10)-connected net with its Point (Schläfli) symbol (42·6)2(44·62)(416·622·87) as simply illustrated in Figure e.

elements.content: The four carboxylate groups of each BTEC4− ligand in complex 3 exhibit two kinds of coordination modes, two in a μ2-η2:η1 fashion and the other two in a μ2-η1:η1 bridging mode (Type III, Scheme ); as a result, each BTEC4− ligand in 3 adopts a μ6-bridging mode. If the connection of L ligand is ignored, each BTEC4− ligand links six Cd(II) atoms to form a 3D structure with 1D channels (Figure b). The size of the channel is about 13.66 × 15.82 Å. On the other hand, each L ligand connects four Cd(II) atoms via its four imidazole groups. The coordinated nitrogen atoms of the L ligand are in the same side of the central benzene ring plane with distances of 2.59 and 3.08 Å between the coordinated nitrogen atom and the benzene ring plane; thus each L ligand looks like a “bowl” (Type II, Scheme and Figure c). The “bowls”, namely, the L ligands, with “up” and “down” orientations are linked together through Cd−N coordination interactions between the L ligand and Cd2O2 subunits, leading to the formation of a (Cd2O2)2-L infinite 1D chain along the c axis (Figure c). The distance between the two benzene ring planes with “up” and “down” orientations within the 1D chain is 11.28 Å. Finally, the (Cd2O2)2-L infinite 1D chains fill into the 3D structure of Cd-BTEC4− leading to the formation of the whole framework structure of 3 (Figure d).

elements.content: The inorganic−organic hybrid coordination polymers with d10 metal centers have been investigated for fluorescence properties with potential applications in chemical sensors, photochemistry, and light-emitting diodes (LEDs). Therefore, the solid-state photoluminescent spectra of compounds 1−5 and free ligands L, H3BTC, H3BTA, H4BTEC were measured at room temperature, and the results are given in . Emissions were observed at 395 nm (λex = 355 nm) for the free H3BTC and 340 nm (λex = 310 nm) for H4BTEC, while no clear luminescence was detected for H3BTA and L ligands as reported previously. The main emission peaks of complexes 1−5 are observed at 426 nm (λex = 364 nm) for 1, 398 nm (λex = 357 nm) for 2, 419 nm (λex = 351 nm) for 3, 430 nm (λex = 337 nm) for 4, and 458 nm (λex =393 nm) for 5. Compared to the free H3BTC, H4BTEC ligand, the emission bands of 1, 3, and 4 are 31, 79, and 35 nm red-shifted, respectively. As to the complexes 2 and 5, clear emissions appeared even though no emissions were detected for L and H3BTA ligands. It is clear that the red-shifted emissions in 1, 3, and 4 and the appearance of emissions in 2 and 5 are caused by coordination of organic ligands to the metal centers. It has been reported that the ligand conformational rigidity may be increased due to their coordination to the metal centers resulting in a decrease in the nonradiative decay of intraligand excited states. Such board emission bands may be tentatively assigned to ligand-to-metal charge transfer (LMCT). In addition, it is noticeable that the emission of complex 5 is quite different from other complexes (), which may be attributed to the different structures and/or crystal packing of the complex in the solid state. The result means that the structure of the complex may have a subtle but significant influence on the luminescent property.

cln_elements.content: Thermogravimetric analyses (TGA) were carried out under N2 atmosphere to examine the thermal stability of complexes 1−5 and the results are shown in Figure . For complex 1, a weight loss of 0.68% was observed below 120 °C which is attributed to the release of the free water molecules (calcd. 0.69%), and then the decomposition of the framework occurred at about 360 °C. Complex 2 showed a weight loss of 4.1% below 165 °C corresponding to the release of coordinated and free water molecules (calcd 4.2%) and the decomposition of the residue was observed at 330 °C. For complex 3, the first weight loss of 2.9% occurred in the temperature range of 20−140 °C, due to the release of free water molecules (calcd 2.6%), and the decomposition of the residue occurs at 370 °C. The TGA curve of 4 shows that the weight loss of 8.2% between 20 and 120 °C is attributed to the release of the coordinated and free water molecules (calcd 8.3%); the residue decomposed at 450 °C. In the case of 5, there is a weight loss of 3.6% (calcd 2.9%), attributed to the release of water molecule between 20 and 110 °C; the residue begins to decompose at 315 °C. It should be noticed that complexes 3 and 4 with rigid multicarboxylate ligands showed higher stability than 2 and 5 with a flexible one of BTA3−, as indicated by their decomposition temperature. Thus, it is important to choose multicarboxylate ligands in the design and synthesis of MOFs with desired stability and properties.
